<br>
Big government/big business approach is fine for marshalling the resources to accomplish special large non-commercially viable projects - Apollo to the Moon, D-Day, etc., but it is a disaster when trying to be efficient and effective. <br>
<br>
I do take some issue with the author's mocking of Langley. It was luck more than anything that prevented him from being the first to fly. His designs needed some modifications (as did Wright's and Curtis's) but he was as good as any of them. Any of the dozens of projects around the world would have had a successful flyer within the timespan of roughly 1890-1910 - an eyeblink in the Big Scheme of Things.<br>
<br>
That quibble aside, I agree with the article's advocacy of the &quot;grassroots&quot; approach to getting things done. <br>
<br>
